:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hatche","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southern): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate, from Middle English <i>haccher(e)</i>, a derivative of <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’. This normally denoted a gate marking the entrance to a forest or other enclosed piece of land, sometimes a floodgate or sluice-gate. Compare   Hatch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatch","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hatch (Bedfordshire, Devon, Hampshire, Somerset, Wiltshire), Hacche in South Molton (Devon), or else a topographic name from residence near a hatch, a gate leading to a forest or sometimes a sluice-gate, from Middle English <i>hacche</i> ‘gate’ (Old English <i>hæcce</i>, Kentish Old English <i>hec(c)</i>). This name has been in Ireland since the 17th century, associated with County Meath and the nearby part of Louth."]},{"name":"Atcher","meanings":["English: variant of   Hatcher  ."]}]},{"name":"Jeffery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Geoffrey  , common in the Middle Ages (as reflected in surnames such as <i>Jefferson</i>). This is now the usual spelling of the name both in North America and Britain. Well-known bearers include the novelist and former British politician  Jeffrey Archer  (  b. 1940 ), the British conductor  Jeffrey Tate  (  b. 1943 ), and the American soul singer  Jeffrey Osborne  (  b. 1951 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffry","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Geoffrey  , common in the Middle Ages (as reflected in surnames such as <i>Jefferson</i>). This is now the usual spelling of the name both in North America and Britain. Well-known bearers include the novelist and former British politician  Jeffrey Archer  (  b. 1940 ), the British conductor  Jeffrey Tate  (  b. 1943 ), and the American soul singer  Jeffrey Osborne  (  b. 1951 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":3,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":12,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":47,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Jeffery de Hatche was born in 1212, in Arlington, Devon, England, his father, Gilbert ad Hacie, was 27 and his mother, Ad Hacie, was 22. He married De Hatche about 1235, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He d